{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613638"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16319"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16319"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9010"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116135"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9010"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16319"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98131"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"},{"type":"tags","id":"7508"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116135"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe bony orbit is a pyramidal space that contains the eye and its supporting structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the proportional volume distribution between the eye and ocular adnexa within the orbit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eye: 4/5, Ocular adnexa: 1/5","Eye: 2/5, Ocular adnexa: 3/5","Eye: 1/2, Ocular adnexa: 1/2","Eye: 1/5, Ocular adnexa: 4/5","Eye: 1/1000, Ocular adnexa: 999/1000"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eeye occupies only one-fifth (1/5)\u003C/strong\u003E of the orbital cavity volume, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Eocular adnexa comprises four-fifths (4/5)\u003C/strong\u003E of the space. This distribution reflects the significant amount of supporting tissue required for proper eye function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4/5 eye to 1/5 adnexa\u003C/strong\u003E represents the inverse of the correct ratio. \u003Cstrong\u003E2/5 eye to 3/5 adnexa\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E1/2 eye to 1/2 adnexa\u003C/strong\u003E both overestimate the eye volume, with the latter significantly overestimating the proportion occupied by the eyeball itself. \u003Cstrong\u003E1/1000 eye to 999/1000 adnexa\u003C/strong\u003E drastically underestimates the eye volume to an unrealistic degree. The ocular adnexa includes extraocular muscles, orbital fat, blood vessels, nerves, and connective tissue, all of which are essential for eye movement, protection, and function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The eyeball only occupies approximately one-fifth (1/5) of the orbital cavity volume.","The remaining four-fifths (4/5) of the orbit contains supporting structures including muscles, fat, vessels, and nerves."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98131"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16319"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"